Sum of questions HH2 through CH7 comprise the U.S. Household Food Security Scale (questions HH2 through AD5a for households with no child present)

Computed variable for households with one or more children:  Raw score zeroâ€”High food security; Raw score 1-2â€”Marginal food security; Raw score 3-7â€”Low food security; Raw score 8-18â€”Very low food security

Computed variable for households with no child present:  Raw score zeroâ€”High food security; Raw score 1-2â€”Marginal food security; Raw score 3-5â€”Low food security; Raw score 6-10â€”Very low food security
Sum of questions HH2 through AD5a comprise the U.S. Adult Food Security Scale.

Computed variable for adults:  Raw score zeroâ€”High food security among adults; Raw score 1-2â€”Marginal food security among adults; Raw score 3-5â€”Low food security among adults; Raw score 6-10â€”Very low food security among adults
Sum of questions HH3 through AD3 comprise the six-item Short Module from which the Six-Item Food Security Scale can be calculated

Computed variable for adult short form:  Raw score 0-1â€”High or marginal food security (raw score 1 may be considered marginal food security, but a large proportion of households that would be measured as having marginal food security using the household or adult scale will have raw score zero on the six-item scale); Raw score 2-4â€”Low food security; Raw score 5-6â€”Very low food security
Sum of questions CH1 through CH7 comprise the U.S. Childrenâ€™s Food Security Scale

Computed variable for children:  Raw score 0-1â€”High or marginal food security among children (raw score 1 may be considered marginal food security, but it is not certain that all households with raw score zero have high food security among children because the scale does not include an assessment of the anxiety component of food insecurity); Raw score 2-4â€”Low food security among children; Raw score 5-8â€”Very low food security among children
